 CERN-TH/2003-087

TPI-MINN-03/10, UMN-TH-2135/03
 
On  -String Tensions and Domain Walls 
in   Gluodynamics   

A. Armoni  and M. Shifman  
adi.armoni, michael.shifman@cern.ch 
 Theory Division, CERN 
CH-1211 Geneva 23, Switzerland 
 William I. Fine Theoretical Physics Institute, University
of Minnesota, 
Minneapolis, MN 55455, USA 
 

We discuss the   dependence of the -string tension  
in SU() supersymmetric gluodynamics. As well known, at large 
  the -string consists, to leading 
order, of  noninteracting fundamental strings, so that
. We argue, both from field-theory
and string-theory side, that subleading corrections to this formula run in
powers of  rather than , thus excluding the Casimir scaling. 
We suggest a heuristic model allowing one
to relate the -string tension in four-dimensional gluodynamics
 with the tension of the
BPS domain walls (-walls).
In this model  the domain walls are made of a net of strings
 connected to each other by baryon vertices.
The relation emerging in this way
leads to the sine formula .
We discuss possible corrections to the sine law, 
and present arguments that they are 
suppressed by  factors. 
We explain
why the sine law does not hold in two dimensions. Finally, we discuss the
applicability
 of the sine formula for non-supersymmetric orientifold field theories.





