both from field theory and string theory side,  that corrections to Eq. ()
run in powers  of . This then leaves no space to the Casimir
scaling in four dimensions.
Second, we suggest a heuristic picture, based on -walls in gluodynamics,
from which Eq. () naturally follows. 

Domain walls are BPS objects in gluodynamics. 
They interpolate between distinct vacua of the theory, say
vacuum  and vacuum  (altogether there are  vacua).
The domain walls interpolating between neighboring vacua are called "elementary,"
while at  we deal with the -walls which can be viewed as bound states
of  elementary walls.

The tension of -walls is known  exactly  ,
   
(note that  is -independent).
The similarity between Eqs. () and ()
is apparent. This becomes more than a mere similarity if one accepts
our qualitative picture:
we suggest that  -walls  can be thought of as being "composed" of 
fluctuating -strings
 connected by baryon vertices (junctions of  strings). This picture
originated from the observation that the wall tension scales as
, at large . Moreover, it is supported by the recent finding
 that a level  Chern-Simons theory lives on the wall. 

Indeed, if our picture is correct, one can easily show that 
T_k  _k  (   N ) + subleading corrections  , 
which leads directly to Eq. () for the -string tension.
We can also reverse the logic: if Eq. () is indeed a good
approximation to the -string tension of gluodynamics - a
-wall can be well approximated by a net of -strings.

The organization of this paper is as follows: in Sect.  we explain
why SU() gauge dynamics leads to  corrections to the leading
-string tension. In Sect.  we present our model and  provide
supporting
arguments both from field theory and string theory. 
Section  is devoted to analysis 
of the  dependence of binding forces
versus  dependence.
A remark concerning non-supersymmetric
Yang-Mills theories is presented in Sect. . 
In  Sect.  we
explain why the two dimensional case and the strong coupling lattice
expansion are special. Section   is devoted
to concluding remarks.


Corrections:   or  ?  

At  both -walls and -strings present ensembles 
of  noninteracting constituents - elementary walls and 
fundamental strings, respectively.
The binding emerges as a subleading in  effect.
The Casimir scaling predicts it at level  while the sine formula
at level . In both cases the binding is weak at large .

The Casimir scaling was abstracted from various models
in which confinement is due to a one-gluon 
exchange(The quadratic Casimir coefficient
