The model 

In this section we outline  our model or, better to say, a heuristic picture
which has been mentioned in the introduction. We use
both field theory and string theory languages.


   
file=wall.eps,width=3.0true cm,angle=0  
  The domain wall 
in supersymmetric gluodynamics
as a net of strings joined via  baryon vertices.
The example above refers to SU(6). One should imagine an irregular lattice of nodes connected
by lines in a chaotic (but planar) way, so that each node either receives or emits  lines. The net fluctuates in the quantum-mechanical sense,
and in no way represents a regular structure similar to fullerenes. 

Field theory picture 

The elementary  wall tension 
in gluodynamics scales  at large 
as . 
One may ask how the factor  appears in the theory
where there are no fields in the fundamental representation of SU(),
only in the adjoint. 
Ordinary solitons scale as . This led Witten to 
suggest that the BPS domain walls at hand are in fact  QCD D-branes. 
A   D-brane signature of the domain walls
is that  QCD strings can end on these domain walls
 (see also)
and parallel walls can exchange glueballs (closed
strings) between them.

This is no explanation on the microscopic field-theoretic level, however.
In a bid to explain the linear  dependence of the 
wall tension in a "natural way" we will assume that
the wall presents a (fluctuating) network of interconnected
-string junctions, as in Fig. . It is known since  long  that
 fundamental strings can join each other in a baryon vertex.
Let us assume that these nodes form a 
flat two-dimensional structure.
Every node either emits or absorbs  fundamental strings.
The strings intertwine the nodes randomly (but in a planar way)
creating an elementary domain wall. If the density of nodes is of order one per
area  of the wall surface, then the tension will naturally scale as
. 

Since the wall is made of -string junctions
we can relate the tension of the wall to the tension of the string.
Indeed, on the one hand, the energy of the square with area 
on the elementary wall is , by definition.
On the other hand, it is of the order of .
Thus, . The axial charge of
the wall is carried by the baryonic junctions (we discuss this issue
in more details in the next subsection). 

Now, let us pass to -strings and -walls.
It is established that  elementary walls
form a bound state, the -wall.
It is also well established that the multiplicity of the -wall is_k = N! k! (N-k)! .
This is also the multiplicity of the antisymmetric  -index representation.
On the other hand, as various arguments indicate,
for -ality 
the lowest energy configuration for two distant groups of 
 fundamental quarks (antiquarks) corresponds to quarks in the
antisymmetric  representation of SU().
This is suggestive that the -wall is built of the 
-strings in the same way as the elementary wall of fundamental strings.
The  wall can be viewed as  a flat two-dimensional 
fluctuating web of nodes
each of which emanates or absorbs  -strings.
Here we assume the existence of the -string junctions, which can be viewed
as bound states of 1-string junctions.

If so,  we arrive
at the relation (). 
Unlike the -wall tension which is given by the sine formula exactly ,
see Eq. (), we do not expect the sine formula to be exact for
the -strings:
 the wall is a BPS object, whereas the QCD string is not.
 
A general function that satisfies the requirements: (i) 
symmetry under  ;
(ii) being even in powers of ;  and (iii)
  tending to   at large , can be written as follows:
N ^2 _odd   l  C_l (N)(  kN  )^l
