with . Since the QCD string is non-BPS, apriori  all  are
non-vanishing.

What can be said of corrections in the right-hand side of Eq. ()?
In the web of  strings forming a -wall, 
 binding interactions in the direction
transverse to the wall plane, which are -dependent,
are contaminated by interactions along the wall plane, which we 
expect to be  independent. That is to say that we expect 




If so, the corrections  in the right-hand side of Eq. ()
are of order . At large  and  fixed, these corrections are then subleading.

We would like to mention a possible difficulty in our model,
a question to be addressed in the future(A.A. thanks
J. Barbon for addressing both the problem and its possible solution.) .
The 1-wall thickness
is ,
whereas the flux-tube thickness is much larger,
 . That is, the QCD 1-string hardly fits the 1-wall
in the perpendicular direction. The thickness of  -walls and  -strings
has not yet been  established. It might well be
that the thickness of both of them at  fixed and 
is the same. This is another
reason why our picture may be successful at large  but definitely
fails at small .

The arguments above certainly do not have the status
of a direct field-theoretical proof of
 Eq. () in  gluodynamics.
They are nevertheless supplementary and independent of other arguments,
such as MQCD-based derivation (it does
not apply to gluodynamics, but, rather, to unknown theories in the 
same universality class),
or the supergravity argument (which holds for theories  having a different
ultraviolet content than gluodynamics). 
The picture we have conjectured  is entirely  within field theory
per se .

String theory picture 

From the string theory point of view our model is rather natural.
For example, in the Polchinski-Strassler supergravity dual,
domain walls are represented by wrapped D5 branes that look
like D2 branes from the 4d point of view. The baryons are wrapped D3 
branes that look effectively like D0 branes. It was even conjectured by
Polchinski and Strassler that "an assembly of baryons can be arranged
into a spherical domain wall!". 


In the type IIA realization
of gluodynamics by Acharya and Vafa, domain walls are
represented by wrapped D4 branes and baryons as wrapped D2 branes.

In both realizations  the wall looks like a D2 brane and the
baryon-vertex as a D0 brane. We suggest that the D2 brane is made
out of D0 branes and fundamental strings that connect them.

Indeed, according the Acharya-Vafa there is a level  
Chern-Simons (CS) term on the wall. The source of this term is the interaction  
term of the D4 with a RR bulk field. Since the D4 wraps an  with
a total RR flux of  units, we get a level  CS term in the 2+1
theory.

The CS term can be viewed as a baryon vertex, if the field
strength on the domain wall is replaced by a delta function. This is
exactly what we obtain by wrapping a D2 over . So, the the
wrapped D4 can be thought of as made out of D2 branes: both serve as 
a source for  fundamental strings.

To conclude, we suggest that the wall (a D-brane) is made out of a net
of lower dimensional D-branes and the strings that connect them. The
tension of the wall is due to the tension of the strings (but also due
to the tension of the D0 branes). 

The axial charge of the wall, that
is the RR charge of the D2 brane, is due to the RR charge of the
D0 branes (the baryon vertices).
This should explain why the order parameter
 changes its phase
when one pierces the wall in passing from left to right or
vice versa .

 It is difficult to understand  how the
wall, which is a BPS object, is built from non-BPS constituents 
(recall that even the wrapped
D2 is not BPS). It means that our construction is approximate. At
large , however, the corrections are expected to be small.

The picture that we advocate in this section is obviously similar to Myers 
effect.

  dependence versus   dependence 

In Sect.  we discussed in detail the structure
of the  corrections responsible for the binding of  1-strings into
a -string. The heuristic picture of "-strings as building blocks for -walls,"
discussed in detail in Sect. , leads, at large , 
to the sine law, Eq. (),
for the -wall tension, which implies not only a very special
 dependence, but a special  dependence too. 
This  dependence may seem counterintuitive, at first sight.
Our task is to invert the argument and see whether we can learn anything new
from this analysis.

Let us start from the -wall tension (), which is the exact result of
gluodynamics. (In the remainder of this section, for simplicity,
we put .) Expanding the sine we get
T_k = N k - ^3 6 k^3 N  + ^5 120 
k^5 N^3 -....
  
The first term represents  noninteracting
1-walls, while the second and higher terms are due to a binding
force. Let us examine the second term, proportional to .
The  dependence tells us that it is due to a binary interaction,
since the domain walls are QCD D-branes, see Ref. .
Naively one would then require
a coefficient  proportional to  rather than , which is just 
a combinatorial factor.
The exact formula tells us that this is impossible. What went wrong?

When we have an ensemble 
of  constituents with  binary interactions (with a coupling )
bound in a "compound nucleus," the binding energy scales
as  only provided that the size of the system and the
coupling  are 
-independent. This is what happens, for instance, in Witten's picture of 
baryons. However, in the case of the domain walls, we have an
ordered system along the line, with a non-universal 
coupling(We thank A. Ritz 
who pointed out to us the importance of the wall
ordering and non-universality of the interaction force.) .
 The coupling
of a wall to its -th neighbor is . The sum over
all possible pairs yields the  behavior. A similar  behavior
 is expected in a one-dimensional system with size  and a linear
potential between pairs. Other examples of one-dimensional ordered
-body systems with the ground state energy scaling as 
are known in the literature, see e.g.
.

As we pass to , the situation may  be rather similar.
In this case the sine law implies
_k =  k - ^3 6 k^3 N^2  + ^5 120 
k^5 N^4 -....
Again, the  dependence of the term
 has the structure typical of binary interactions.
A "natural"   dependence in this case, as was mentioned, is .
This "natural"  factor follows from a
picture of a "compound state" with a typical size being -independent.
Basing on the lesson of -walls we are
inclined to think that a more complicated  scaling takes place due
to a -dependence of a typical size of
 the cross-section of the -string.


What can be said about non-supersymmetric gauge theories? 

Above we presented a model yielding
 a relation between the -wall and -string tensions
in gluodynamics. It is natural to ask now
about  non-supersymmetric gauge theories, in particular,
the orientifold theory discussed in Ref. . 
In this theory, the gluino adjoint field is replaced by
a Dirac two-index field in the antisymmetric representation, which, obviously,
makes it non-supersymmetric.
The orientifold theory was shown to be planar
equivalent to gluodynamics
in the mutually overlapping sectors. At large  
both have  discrete vacua and  domain walls of a very similar structure.
This may suggest that the -string tension in the
non-supersymmetric orientifold theory is described
by the same sine formula as in gluodynamics.

At first sight this suggestion looks heretical.
Indeed, in  gluodynamics any -index source cannot be screened,
and, therefore, develops a string.
On the other hand, in the orientifold theory,
any source with even  can be completely screened by dynamical 
quarks. Any source with odd  can be almost screened -
only one fundamental index remains unscreened.
Common wisdom prompts one 
that there is no place for such quantity as  in this
theory.

Let us remember, however,  that our argument in favor of the
sine formula refers to large , namely,  at  (we can obtain no result
otherwise). At large , in order to screen the
-index source, one has to (pair)produce
 a large number of dynamical quarks, scaling as
,  from the
vacuum.
This process is suppressed, presumably exponentially, as
 where  is a positive number
(we are  certain that it is at least power suppressed).
Thus, at large  there is confinement in the 
orientifold theory,  , and, according to our
hypothesis, obeys the sine law.


Why two-dimensional Yang-Mills theory 

and strong coupling lattice expansion 

are special? 

In two-dimensional Yang-Mills theory the "-string tension"
is known exactly, and it
obeys the Casimir scaling,
 . 
A question which immediately comes to one's mind is "what makes two-dimensional 
formula special?"

The answer is as follows. Genuine strings, with local interaction
(such as those one deals with in four dimensions) never develop in two dimensions.
The two-dimensional  Yang-Mills theory (in the axial gauge) is free, Gaussian.
Non-linearity is absent, and so are transverse dimensions. Confinement is 
due to the one-gluon exchange (instantaneous in time) which provides a linear potential
with the coefficient proportional to the Casimir operator .
As a reflection of the absence of the bona fide  strings in two dimensions,
please, observe that the "-string tension"
 depends in this case
on the specific representation and not  merely  on the -ality.

The same situation takes place in a variety of ad hoc 
four-dimensional models where (a modified) one-gluon exchange
is postulated to be responsible for confinement.
In these models the gluon propagator at small momenta
is assumed to scale as  rather than .
This certainly provides a linear confinement with the 
coefficient. This approach is totally inconsistent
with our arguments.

The situation in (four-dimensional)
lattice strong coupling expansion
 is similar to that in 
two-dimensional Yang-Mills theory.
As well-known, see e.g., the strong coupling Wilson expansion
implies a linear confinement with the coefficient in front
of the linear potential determined by . The "1-strings"
 do not interact "in the bulk." Therefore, we do  not have a bona fide 
1-string binding of the type we expect in actual 
four-dimensional Yang-Mills theory, where the scale
parameter is dynamically generated, 
and the attraction of 1-strings (per unit length)
is localized along the string.


Discussion and conclusions 

The main thrust of this paper is on the model presenting the BPS -wall in 
gluodynamics as a planar  network of baryonic vertices (nodes)
connected by  -strings. The network is irregular and fluctuating.
The model is admittedly heuristic and qualitative.
Taking it at  its face value, however, one can 
get a relation between the -wall tension which is exactly
known, and the -string tension.
 
Our relation implies the Douglas-Shenker sine formula.
Irrespective of particular models is the result
we have proven en route : the  corrections to the free string limit,
, run in powers of  rather than .
This rules out the Casimir scaling.
In general,  models with linear confinement 
basically fall into two categories.
The coefficient in front of the linear term in the potential between 
two probe objects in the given model may either depend on a particular color representation
of the probe object, or only on the -ality.
In the first class of models corrections to
 run in powers of .
In the second class, which  includes four-dimensional Yang-Mills
theory, corrections run in powers of . Note that
in the first class of models,
it is wrong to label the string tension only by the -ality . One should  indicate the
corresponding Young tableau for the particular color representation 
of the probe object.

The central question in the issue of the
-string tension is the nature and size of corrections to the sine formula.
We presented an argument showing that at  fixed and 
these corrections are suppressed by  factors, i.e.  suppressed
parametrically.
On the other hand, 
one of the backgrounds considered in Ref. (the Klebanov-Strassler background) leads to corrections 
to the sine formula which are
strongly suppressed numerically, but not parametrically.
Is it due to the fact that the ultraviolet behavior of the AdS/CFT
models is different from that in gluodynamics?
The question remains open. Moreover, recently it was argued  
that in (1+2)-dimensional Yang-Mills theory
corrections to the sine formula are so large that they, in fact, convert it
into a (well) approximated Casimir formula 
for the background of Cvetic  et al.  , an analog of the Klebanov-Strassler
background. It is curious that
 for the (1+2)-dimensional analog of the Maldacena-Nun ez
supergravity background 
(see Ref. ) a sine formula is 
suggested in Ref. . From our standpoint, the
only difference between
the (1+2)-dimensional and (1+3)-dimensional gauge theories
is due to the fact that in 1+3 dimensions the mass scale is dynamically
generated (via dimensional transmutation), while in 1+2 dimensions
the mass scale is given by the square of the
gauge coupling constant. In both cases non-linearities are well-developed,
and the spacial string structure is "local." In other words,
the Casimir scaling behavior looks suspicious,
 and, in fact, we expect that in 1+2 dimensions 
large- corrections to 
run in powers of , much in the same way as in
 1+3 dimensions. 
 
It is important to note that our consideration is fully invertible.
If in the future someone succeeds in deriving the
Douglas-Shenker sine formula from other principles,
this will simultaneously substantiate our picture
of the BPS domain -walls made of  fluctuating networks of -strings.


